{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-opus-4-8","id":"msg_011Ccw3eHNBUrAHKnmGXmwS3","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"text","text":"The `--dry-run` flag (short form `-n`) makes rsync simulate a transfer without actually changing anything. It walks through the entire operation and reports exactly what it *would* do — which files would be copied, updated, or deleted — but no files are written, modified, or removed on either end.\n\nIt's most commonly used as a safety check before a real sync, especially when `--delete` is involved (since a misconfigured source path can wipe out files on the destination).\n\n```bash\nrsync -avn --delete src/ dest/     # preview\nrsync -av  --delete src/ dest/     # run for real once it looks right\n```\n\nA few practical notes:\n\n- **Pair it with `-v` (verbose) or `-i` (itemize).** On its own, `-n` still produces output, but `-v`/`-i` make the preview far more readable. `-i` gives a per-file change summary (e.g. `>f+++++++++` for a new file).\n- **The file list can differ slightly from the real run.** Because no data actually moves, rsync sometimes can't compute exact sizes/checksums, so a dry run is an accurate preview of *which* files change, but not always a byte-perfect one.\n- **Great for validating `--delete`, `--exclude`, and filter rules** before committing to them."}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":2,"cache_creation_input_tokens":5092,"cache_read_input_tokens":16998,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":5092},"output_tokens":7,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"diagnostics":null,"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"71698ada-6f35-4f60-95c2-e83584172b8c","uuid":"45c819da-c9ca-4e1a-88e1-5ddbe47b0248","request_id":"req_011Ccw3eGWab7aZbGewkb2KJ"}
